        <h2>Course Syllabus</h2>

        <h3>Module 1: Fundamentals of Epidemiology (Weeks 1 - 4)</h3>
        <p>This module provides a grounding in epidemiological study designs and measures of disease risk used in aetiological epidemiology and health services research.</p>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th style="width: 20%;">Week</th>
                    <th style="width: 40%;">Prework & Reading (2 hrs)</th>
                    <th style="width: 40%;">Lecture Topics (1 hr)</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>1. Introduction to Population Health</strong></td>
                    <td>• Historical context of epidemiology<br>• The clinical vs. population perspective</td>
                    <td>• Overview of the fundamentals of epidemiology<br>• Introduction to epidemiology for doctors<br>• The epidemiological focus: cases and populations</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>2. Measuring Disease</strong></td>
                    <td>• Interpreting incidence and prevalence rates<br>• Overview of health surveillance systems</td>
                    <td>• Measures of disease occurrence<br>• Routine data use in epidemiology</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>3. Measuring Effect</strong></td>
                    <td>• Understanding risk, rates, and odds<br>• Recognizing bias and confounding</td>
                    <td>• Measures of effect and impact<br>• Introduction to causal inference</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>4. Study Design</strong></td>
                    <td>• Hierarchy of clinical evidence<br>• Case studies on clinical trials</td>
                    <td>• Measures of study design (Observational vs. Experimental)<br>• Selecting the right design for your question</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Module 2: Statistics for Epidemiology (Weeks 5 - 8)</h3>
        <p>Master the core biostatistical tools required for analyzing clinical data, understanding probabilities, and conducting valid statistical inferences.</p>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th style="width: 20%;">Week</th>
                    <th style="width: 40%;">Prework & Reading (2 hrs)</th>
                    <th style="width: 40%;">Lecture Topics (1 hr)</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>5. Data Fundamentals</strong></td>
                    <td>• Identifying categorical vs. continuous data<br>• Best practices in data visualization</td>
                    <td>• Introduction to statistics for epidemiology<br>• Data types, summary, and presentations</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>6. Probability & Distributions</strong></td>
                    <td>• The concept of randomness in clinical trials<br>• Recognizing normal distribution curves</td>
                    <td>• Probability and the role of chance<br>• Normal and binomial distributions</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>7. Statistical Inference</strong></td>
                    <td>• Hypothesis testing basics<br>• Understanding Type I and Type II errors</td>
                    <td>• Principles of statistical inference<br>• Comparisons of two means and proportions</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>8. Associations & Effect</strong></td>
                    <td>• Correlation vs. causation<br>• Interpreting confidence intervals</td>
                    <td>• Association of two variables<br>• Statistical measures of effect (p-values and CIs)</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Module 3: Introduction to Scientific Writing (Weeks 9 - 12)</h3>
        <p>Explore structured approaches for research dissemination, focusing on synthesizing your findings into a coherent, publishable manuscript.</p>
        <table>
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th style="width: 20%;">Week</th>
                    <th style="width: 40%;">Prework & Reading (2 hrs)</th>
                    <th style="width: 40%;">Lecture Topics (1 hr)</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>9. The Manuscript Blueprint</strong></td>
                    <td>• Deconstructing a highly-cited paper<br>• The IMRAD structure</td>
                    <td>• Overview of research manuscripts<br>• A dive into manuscript sections: Introduction & Methods</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>10. Presenting the Evidence</strong></td>
                    <td>• Strategies for transparent reporting<br>• Guidelines for tables and figures</td>
                    <td>• A dive into manuscript sections: Results & Discussion<br>• Aligning data with narrative</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>11. The Mechanics of Good Writing</strong></td>
                    <td>• Active vs. passive voice in science<br>• Eliminating clinical jargon</td>
                    <td>• Sentence and paragraph construction for a coherent message<br>• Ensuring logical flow and brevity</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><strong>12. The Publication Journey</strong></td>
                    <td>• Journal selection criteria<br>• Ethics, authorship, and citations</td>
                    <td>• Navigating the peer-review process<br>• Responding to reviewer feedback</td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

